    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-24T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-24T23:00:00-05:00" n="246"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d246">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">845.00/7–2544: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-25T00:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 25, 1944—midnight</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5828. For the Ambassador and Phillips. Drew Pearson’s column today prints large
                    part of Phillips letter to President<note n="26" xml:id="d246fn26">Dated May 14,
                        1943, <ref target="frus1943v04#pg_220">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1943, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 220</ref>.</note> on Indian situation
                    in which he advocated that British King Emperor issue declaration with respect
                    to later independence for India after the war.</p>
                <p>This publication was made without any prior knowledge of the Department and we do
                    not know how Pearson came into possession of copy of this letter addressed to
                    the President.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
